            <h4>Taikien Cooper</h4>
            <p>With a deep passion and strong commitment to local politics, Taikein Cooper is devoted to helping citizens effectively engage in the American political process. 

Born in the historic Prince Edward County, one of five counties in the landmark Brown v. Board of Education case, Cooper is a 2006 graduate from both Southside Virginia Community College and Prince Edward County High School. Aside from pursuing his higher education at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, Cooper has remained politically and physically vested to the Commonwealth of Virginia. 

Devotion and interest in his community dates back to the age of 11, when Cooper canvassed the local community assisting his former D.A.R.E. (Drug Abuse Resistance Education) teacher, Travis Harris, in his campaign to become Prince Edward County's Sheriff. 

Cooper's political involvement seeped into his college years, where he led various political action committees, served on the prestigious Chancellor's Search Committee and even led a grassroots effort to Jena, Louisiana, calling for justice for the infamous Jena Six.

In 2010, after being awarded a degree in Public Policy Analysis from the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, Cooper returned to his true passion, fighting for the betterment of the people of Virginia; this time equipped with more experience, growth and awareness. Having had the opportunity to hold a position as a counselor in a correctional center in Chesapeake, VA, Cooper experienced and attested to the impact of political decisions and their direct correlation on the social welfare of constituents.  

Cooper's personal campaign experiences have brought forth even more drive and inspiration, both on a personal and community-based level. Most notably in 2012, Cooper ran in a special election for Prince Edward County's Treasurer at the age of 24. Throughout his campaign, his age remained a prevalent topic of discussion, given that many young adults are not active in political affairs. The significant number of youth and young adults, who became inspired and energized during his campaign, became a driving force for him. These individuals were compelled and inspired by Cooper's political activism, just as his audience in return inspired him. From this movement, Cooper began to engage the younger generation in his campaign, igniting within them both political and goal oriented motivation. At the age of 25, Cooper was asked to run for US Congress in Virginia's 5th Congressional District.

Cooper recently resigned as the Chief Executive Officer of a private behavioral agency, which served nearly 100 clients throughout the Commonwealth. This decision came at the forward progress to enhance his personal consulting firm. Since the election, Cooper has been speaking at universities and colleges, community rallies and other local institutions across the nation, about the importance and power of young adults in today's political environment and the importance of living for YOU. 
</p>
